                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d525">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">867N.00/364: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul at Jerusalem</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wadsworth</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-08-27T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >August 27, 1936—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Following is text of telegram of August 27 from American Ambassador at London:
                        <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Foreign Office states that the High Commissioner in Palestine has been
                            instructed to extend to the American Senators every practicable courtesy
                            but that the question of their freedom to travel in the country is one
                            entirely in the discretion of the High Commissioner himself.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>In this connection, and with particular reference to the final sentence of the
                    Department’s August 22, 3 p.m., you will, of course, appreciate that the
                    Department has expressed neither approval nor disapproval of the unofficial
                    mission on which the Senators are engaged.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
